Customer Churn: Telecom Dataset¶

Customer churn or customer turnover means the loss of an existing customers.
Because the cost of retaining an existing customer is significantly cheaper than obtaining a new one, organizations frequently do their hardest to retain customers utilizing various analyses and customer attrition rates as one of their major business indicators. Companies in these industries frequently have customer service branches that strive to reclaim customers, because recovered long-term customers are worth far more to a company than freshly obtained customers.
Typically, businesses distinguish between voluntary and involuntary churn. Involuntary churn happens when a client chooses to switch to another company or service provider, while voluntary churn occurs when a customer is forced to move to a long-term care facility, dies, or moves to a new area. In most cases, unintentional reasons for churn are not taken into account in analytical models. Analysts tend to focus on voluntary churn since it is generally caused by aspects of the company-customer relationship that are under the company's control, such as how billing contacts are handled or how after-sales support is offered.
Turnover prediction models are used in predictive analytics to anticipate customer attrition by measuring their risk of churn. These models are successful in focusing customer retention marketing activities on the fraction of the customer base that is most prone to churn because they generate a short prioritized list of probable defectors.

Train Test Split¶










In [17]:



     


from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

target_col = ['Churn']
cols=[i for i in df.columns if i not in target_col]
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df[cols], df['Churn'],stratify= df['Churn'],
                                                    test_size =0.3, random_state = 100)
print(colored("Dimension of Train Data :", 'blue', attrs=['bold']), x_train.shape)

Decision Tree¶










In [18]:



     


from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix

DT = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 100,splitter = "best", criterion = "gini")
DT.fit(x_train,y_train)

y_pred_prob_dt = DT.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1]
fpr_dt, tpr_dt, thresholds_dt = roc_curve(y_test, DT.predict(x_test))
roc_auc_dt = auc(fpr_dt, tpr_dt)
precision_dt, recall_dt, th_dt = precision_recall_curve(y_test, DT.predict(x_test))

print(colored("Classification Report:", 'blue', attrs=['bold']))
print(classification_report(y_test,DT.predict(x_test),target_names=["Not churn", "Churn"]))
print(colored("Confusion Matrix:", 'blue', attrs=['bold']))
sns.heatmap(
    confusion_matrix(y_test, DT.predict(x_test)),
    annot=True,
    fmt="d",
    xticklabels=["Not churn", "Churn"],
    yticklabels=["Not churn", "Churn"]
)

Feature Importance¶










In [19]:



     


def feature_importance(algo,x_train):
    coefficients = pd.DataFrame(algo.feature_importances_)
    column_df = pd.DataFrame(x_train.columns.tolist())
    coef_sumry = (pd.merge(coefficients, column_df, left_index=True, right_index=True, how="left"))
    coef_sumry.columns = ["coefficients", "features"]
    coef_sumry = coef_sumry.sort_values(by = "coefficients", ascending=False)
    sns.barplot(x="coefficients", y="features", data=coef_sumry)
    return()
print(colored("Feature Importance:", 'blue', attrs=['bold']))

Performance of the Models over Training Dataset¶










In [21]:



     


models = {'Decision Tree': [DT, cols], 'SVM (rbf)': [SVM, cols]}
def model_report(model, training_x, testing_x, training_y, testing_y, name):
    model = model.fit(training_x, training_y)
    predictions = model.predict(testing_x)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(testing_y, predictions)
    recallscore = recall_score(testing_y, predictions)
    precision = precision_score(testing_y, predictions)
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(testing_y, predictions)
    f1score = f1_score(testing_y, predictions) 
    kappa_metric = cohen_kappa_score(testing_y, predictions)
    
    df = pd.DataFrame({"Model"           : [name],
                       "Accuracy"        : [accuracy],
                       "Recall"          : [recallscore],
                       "Precision"       : [precision],
                       "f1-score"        : [f1score],
                       "Roc_auc"         : [roc_auc],
                       "Kappa_metric"    : [kappa_metric],
                      })
    return df

k-fold Crossvalidation¶










In [25]:



     


from sklearn import model_selection
models = []
criterion=['gini', 'entropy']
splitter=['best','random']
max_features=['auto','sqrt','log2']
for c in criterion:
    for s in splitter:
        for m in max_features:
            models.append(('DT '+' '+str(c)+' '+str(s)+' '+str(m), 
                           DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion=c,splitter=s,max_features=m,random_state = 100)))
kernel=['linear', 'poly', 'rbf', 'sigmoid']
gamma=['scale', 'auto']
for k in kernel:
    for g in gamma:
        models.append(('SVM '+' '+str(k)+' '+str(g), SVC(C=10,kernel=k,gamma=g,random_state = 100)))



     















Evaluating each model in turn¶










In [26]:



     


results = []
names = []
scoring = 'f1'
for name, model in models:
    kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=10)
    cv_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(model, df.iloc[:,:13],df['Churn'].to_numpy(), cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,6))
fig.suptitle('Algorithm Comparison')
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
plt.boxplot(results)
ax.set_xticklabels(names,rotation=45)
plt.show()
